d or in Europe, Kervégan shows how Hegel—often associated with grand metaphysical ideas—actually had a specific conception of civil society and the state. In Hegel’s view, public institutions represent the fulfillment of deep subjective needs—and in that sense, demonstrate that the real is the rational, because what surrounds us is the product of our collective mindedness. This groundbreaking analysis will guide the study of Hegel and nineteenth-century political thought for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aObjectivity. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSubjectivity. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aHegel.  agerman classical philosophy.  ainstitutionalism.  aphilosophy of law.  apolitical philosophy.  arights.1 aGinsburg, Daniela.1 aShuster, Martin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226023946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226023946/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles